    <title>The Sequence of Primes</title>
    <content type='html'>&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiKQIQps_ofQlG8fN1vQmCMh6hdX6CZlaUpvXhWohvz3XSdPOcgLytM1mhjUNByum-a9J9mUpt7N_BUrckhV37aH3wkWto9F2YPlfAYdwKIrdm1L2wc2leajEeOKHpWgbf3AwcdW2Xx8ss/s1600-h/tinker_distribution.jpg"&gt;&lt;img style="display:block; margin:0px auto 10px; text-align:center;cursor:pointer; cursor:hand;width: 400px; height: 134px;" src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiKQIQps_ofQlG8fN1vQmCMh6hdX6CZlaUpvXhWohvz3XSdPOcgLytM1mhjUNByum-a9J9mUpt7N_BUrckhV37aH3wkWto9F2YPlfAYdwKIrdm1L2wc2leajEeOKHpWgbf3AwcdW2Xx8ss/s400/tinker_distribution.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5297166837166324386" /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: left;"&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div style="text-align: left;"&gt;As I make my way through Hardy &amp;amp; Wright's &lt;a href="http://books.google.com/books?id=FlUj0Rk_rF4C&amp;amp;printsec=frontcover"&gt;An Introduction to the Theory of Numbers,&lt;/a&gt;  I am hoping to work it into my recreational math pursuits - coming up with interesting (but not too heavy) activities that correspond roughly to the material in the text.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;The first two chapters are on the sequence of primes. Here's the activity: obtain a list of primes, import them into &lt;a href="http://www.keypress.com/x5656.xml"&gt;Fathom&lt;/a&gt;, and construct plots that explore &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;p&lt;/span&gt;n and &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;pi&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;) and other aspects of the sequence that manifest themselves in the first couple of thousand terms.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;Here is one of the places you can get your list of primes: &lt;a href="http://primes.utm.edu/"&gt;http://primes.utm.edu/&lt;/a&gt;. In my Fathom experiment, I imported the first 2262 prime numbers.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;If you import a sequential list of primes into Fathom (under the attribute &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;prime&lt;/span&gt;) and add another attribute&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt; n=caseindex&lt;/span&gt;, you can create two nice plots. Plot A should have &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;prime &lt;/span&gt;as the &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; axis and &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;  as the &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold; "&gt;&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: normal; "&gt;&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; axis. This shows the function &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;pi&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;). To this plot you should add the function &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;y &lt;/span&gt;= &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;/&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;ln&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;) and visually compare the two curves. Plot B should have the &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; axis reversed. On this graph, plotting the function &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;y&lt;/span&gt; = &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;*&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;ln&lt;/span&gt;(&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;x&lt;/span&gt;) shows how closely this approximation for &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;p&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt; (the &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-style: italic;"&gt;n&lt;/span&gt;th prime) comes to the actual values.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhJJwUIHhJmVVzq3KXVRLlSsdjVUOD_tjEqBkX2ZcLs0uPvI1dMfV71-5ZlmhOndP8MvAvIPBH5kQi3KAKIlJDm1kZrRmQme68js7hBz_Omy0kG-PyXjZhaRW0s-fdGDzwyReUwUhMp-8U/s1600-h/pi_approx.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEhJJwUIHhJmVVzq3KXVRLlSsdjVUOD_tjEqBkX2ZcLs0uPvI1dMfV71-5ZlmhOndP8MvAvIPBH5kQi3KAKIlJDm1kZrRmQme68js7hBz_Omy0kG-PyXjZhaRW0s-fdGDzwyReUwUhMp-8U/s400/pi_approx.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5297161129264438034" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 400px; height: 239px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjo3WjAE9J1hlnoFKsUdApPm77kjSb_9Q-gXqWHWhwm0JnEUOku3iISNEqNlBVCbnZE9Dcw26yAvypZeQXjfgTg0CQK32X_BG_wF_n8-HcFZTfGjlkd-RmxWwUcuQOM94sKjPF2H3KihIU/s1600-h/tinker_distribution.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjo3WjAE9J1hlnoFKsUdApPm77kjSb_9Q-gXqWHWhwm0JnEUOku3iISNEqNlBVCbnZE9Dcw26yAvypZeQXjfgTg0CQK32X_BG_wF_n8-HcFZTfGjlkd-RmxWwUcuQOM94sKjPF2H3KihIU/s1600-h/tinker_distribution.jpg"&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjomLb-3jP7EDGoR6amsL00LKp7knfpwsMI_LOFzktSoctrahD-RRaoIYjwkyhpz2bhvb5pRlmNtoiNvJxY_YDCAUF2IUIQZWjS5B8d9_cLElyAgx9aie3iJSlE0AWTmTHIv1M6UEI5GsA/s1600-h/pn_approx.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEjomLb-3jP7EDGoR6amsL00LKp7knfpwsMI_LOFzktSoctrahD-RRaoIYjwkyhpz2bhvb5pRlmNtoiNvJxY_YDCAUF2IUIQZWjS5B8d9_cLElyAgx9aie3iJSlE0AWTmTHIv1M6UEI5GsA/s400/pn_approx.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5297161135138846690" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 400px; height: 220px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;You can add further attributes to look at the distance between primes &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;dist=prime-prev(prime)&lt;/span&gt;, and also the frequency of twin primes &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;is_twin = (dist=2)or(next(dist)=2)&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style=""&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;a onblur="try {parent.deselectBloggerImageGracefully();} catch(e) {}" href="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiouh_vAYGqad8b9Y2JkrtkpzH_mDwbJCVOcuIJxgA8Zaq3kbQUN7eRRGOf4Zp4uK5UVlyQO3VEoBdc_c5uiIiJyAX6-gDSonVyWlzAwwphrFIt8CTCVXLnS-bNgHglZ16dK3QdXKpDetQ/s1600-h/twin_ratio.jpg"&gt;&lt;img src="https://blogger.googleusercontent.com/img/b/R29vZ2xl/AVvXsEiouh_vAYGqad8b9Y2JkrtkpzH_mDwbJCVOcuIJxgA8Zaq3kbQUN7eRRGOf4Zp4uK5UVlyQO3VEoBdc_c5uiIiJyAX6-gDSonVyWlzAwwphrFIt8CTCVXLnS-bNgHglZ16dK3QdXKpDetQ/s400/twin_ratio.jpg" border="0" alt="" id="BLOGGER_PHOTO_ID_5297161133546183858" style="display: block; margin-top: 0px; margin-right: auto; margin-bottom: 10px; margin-left: auto; text-align: center; cursor: pointer; width: 400px; height: 279px; " /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;You can also add attributes to keep a running count of &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;twin_primes&lt;/span&gt;, and to keep a running average of the &lt;span class="Apple-style-span" style="font-weight: bold;"&gt;twin_primes&lt;/span&gt;. The plot above shows how the ratio of tiwn primes diminishes as the number of primes increases. The plot at the top of the post was made by bringing the same data into &lt;a href="http://www.keypress.com/x5715.xml"&gt;Tinkerplots &lt;/a&gt;- it suggests the distribution of primes and twin primes (in blue) in the numbers up to the 2262nd prime.&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;div&gt;&lt;br /&gt;&lt;/div&gt;</content>
